HEADWORD: Flow
<hw>Flow</hw> <pr>(fl⟦omac⟧)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <def><pos>imp.
sing.</pos> of <er>Fly</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos></def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flow
<hw>Flow</hw> <pr>(fl⟦omac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Flowed</conjf> <pr>(fl⟦omac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Flowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>fl⟦omac⟧wan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>vloeijen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>flawen</ets> to wash, Icel. <ets>fl⟦omac⟧a</ets> to deluge, Gr.
<grk>plw`ein</grk> to float, sail, and prob. ultimately to E.
<ets>float</ets>, <ets>fleet</ets>. ⟦root⟧80. Cf. <er>Flood</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To move with a continual change of place among the
particles or parts, as a fluid; to change place or circulate, as a
liquid; <as>as, rivers <ex>flow</ex> from springs and lakes; tears
<ex>flow</ex> from the eyes.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become liquid; to melt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mountains <qex>flowed</qex> down at thy presence.</q>
<rj><qau>Is. lxiv. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To proceed; to issue forth; <as>as, wealth
<ex>flows</ex> from industry and economy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those thousand decencies that daily <qex>flow</qex>⟦br⟧
From all her words and actions.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To glide along smoothly, without harshness or
asperities; <as>as, a <ex>flowing</ex> period; <ex>flowing</ex>
numbers</as>; to sound smoothly to the ear; to be uttered
easily.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Virgil is sweet and <qex>flowing</qex>in his hexameters.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To have or be in abundance; to abound; to full, so
as to run or flow over; to be copious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In that day . . . the hills shall <qex>flow</qex> with milk.</q>
<rj><qau>Joel iii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The exhilaration of a night that needed not the influence of the
<qex>flowing</qex> bowl.</q> <rj><qau>Prof. Wilson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To hang loose and waving; <as>as, a <ex>flowing</ex>
mantle; <ex>flowing</ex> locks.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The imperial purple <qex>flowing</qex> in his train.</q>
<rj><qau>A. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To rise, as the tide; -- opposed to <xex>ebb</xex>;
<as>as, the tide <ex>flows</ex> twice in twenty-four
hours</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The river hath thrice <qex>flowed</qex>, no ebb between.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To discharge blood in excess from the
uterus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flow
<hw>Flow</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover with water or
other liquid; to overflow; to inundate; to flood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cover with varnish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Flow
<hw>Flow</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A stream of water or other
fluid; a current; <as>as, a <ex>flow</ex> of water; a <ex>flow</ex> of
blood.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A continuous movement of something abundant; <as>as,
a <ex>flow</ex> of words</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any gentle, gradual movement or procedure of
thought, diction, music, or the like, resembling the quiet, steady
movement of a river; a stream.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The feast of reason and the <qex>flow</qex> of soul.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The tidal setting in of the water from the ocean to
the shore. See <cref>Ebb and flow</cref>, under <er>Ebb</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A low-lying piece of watery land; -- called also
<altname>flow moss</altname> and <altname>flow bog</altname>.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark> <rj><au>Jamieson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flowage</ent>⟦br⟧
